# JIRA write permissions

## Rule
Agents may perform exactly these JIRA operations and no others:

| Allowed | Forbidden |
|---|---|
| Read tickets, fields, comments, attachments | Create / delete / archive tickets, sub-tasks, epics |
| Add a new comment on a ticket | Delete or hide any comment (own or others') |
| Update a comment **the agent itself authored** | Update or edit a comment authored by a human |
| Read project / board / sprint metadata | Create, modify, or delete projects, boards, sprints, workflows |
| Read ticket transitions / status | Transition / change ticket status (the pipeline never moves a ticket) |
| — | Delete or modify attachments, links, watchers, assignees, labels, fix-versions |

**Delete is universally forbidden.** No agent under any command may delete any JIRA entity (ticket, sub-task, comment, attachment, link, label, board, project, sprint, version, anything), even if the developer explicitly requests it.

## Refusal phrase
If a developer asks for any delete operation in JIRA, the agent must respond verbatim:

> It is not allowed for me to delete anything in JIRA. I can only read information and add/update comments.

No paraphrasing, no "but I can do X instead" follow-up unless the developer asks a new question.

## Why
- Deletes are irreversible. A wrong-target delete on a JIRA ticket destroys audit trail the team relies on for compliance, billing, and incident review.
- Comments are append-only by convention — humans on the team expect their comments to persist as written.
- The pipeline already has the access it needs: read for intake, comment-write for review findings and failure notices. Anything beyond that is out of scope for AI agents.

## Constraints
- Credentials (`JIRA_API_TOKEN`) granted to agents must have a JIRA role that lacks delete and admin permissions at the API level — defense in depth. If the developer's token has broader permissions, agents still must not exercise them.
- The orchestrator (`/implement`, `/bugfix`) is the single writer for review-finding comments — individual review agents return findings to the orchestrator and never call the JIRA API themselves.
- A comment-update is only legal when the comment was authored by the same agent in the same pipeline run (e.g., correcting a typo before Gate 2 fires). Edits to historical comments are forbidden even if AI-authored.
- Refusal applies even inside a `revise <notes>` reply — if the notes contain a delete request, the agent refuses that part and asks the developer to remove or rephrase.

## Examples

### Good
> Developer: "drop the duplicate sub-task EFP-1423-a, it was created by mistake"
> Agent: *It is not allowed for me to delete anything in JIRA. I can only read information and add/update comments.*

> Review pipeline finishes. Orchestrator posts ONE consolidated comment listing all 14 reviewer findings (see [human-approval-gates](human-approval-gates.md)).

### Bad
> Agent silently transitions EFP-1423 from `To Do` to `In Progress` when `/implement` starts.

> Review-agent posts 14 separate comments to the ticket instead of returning findings to the orchestrator.

> Agent edits a comment a human PM wrote two weeks ago to "fix a typo."

